%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Introduction}
%******************************************************************************

The goal of this book is to present with full details the source code of
a {network stack}.

%claude:
``Network stack'' means more than just TCP/IP. In this book it
refers to the whole vertical slice of code that turns an
[[open("/net/tcp/clone", ...)]] call on one machine into a
series of Ethernet frames on a wire and back: the device
driver for the NIC, the Ethernet medium layer, ARP for local
address resolution, IP for routing and fragmentation, UDP/IL/TCP
for transport, and the file-based control plane
([[/net/ipifc/]], [[/net/arp]], [[/net/iproute]]) that lets
user-space programs like [[ipconfig]] configure all of it. The
\plan stack implements that whole vertical in about
10\,000 lines of C, which is the main reason it fits in a book.

\section{Motivations}

Why a network stack? Because I think you are a better programmer if
you fully understand how things work under the hood.
% and nowaday, internet is everything. Most programs use networks.
% even remote app back with browser.

%history?
% Alto again? precursor?
% Then internet.

%claude:
Nowadays, nearly every program communicates over a network.
Web browsers, databases, chat applications, cloud services---they
all depend on the network stack to deliver data reliably between
machines. Yet most programmers treat the network as a black box:
they call [[dial()]] or [[connect()]] and trust that packets
will arrive. Understanding the internals of a network stack
removes that mystery and gives you a much better mental model
for diagnosing network problems, writing performant servers,
and understanding protocols.

Here are a few questions I hope this book will answer:
\begin{itemize}

\item What happens when you open a connection to another machine?

\item How are opened connections stored in the kernel? 

\item How can the kernel dispatch incoming packets to the
right process?

\item How can the network stack offer reliable communications over an 
unreliable physical network?

\end{itemize}
