\section{The \plan network stack: [[/net]]}

% I chose plan9 network stack. Again partly for consistency. But again
% because cleaner I think. Also IL is easier to explain than TCP
% while conveying its most important ideas.

% talk also about ndb and ipconfig applications?
% maybe telnet?

%claude:
I will explain in this book the code of the \plan network stack,
which is implemented entirely in the kernel behind the
[[/net/]] file interface. The stack includes Ethernet, IP,
ARP, routing, UDP, IL (\plan's own reliable transport protocol),
and TCP. In total, the networking code is roughly
10\,000 lines of C.
%
Like for most books in \principia, I chose a \plan program because
those programs are simple, small, elegant, open source, and they form
together a coherent set.
%
The \plan network stack has an unusual and elegant property:
every network connection is a directory of files. Opening a
connection means creating a directory under [[/net/tcp/]] or
[[/net/udp/]], and communicating means reading and writing files
in that directory. There are no sockets, no [[ioctl]]---just
the same [[open]]/[[read]]/[[write]] interface used for everything
else in \plan.
%
Another advantage is that \plan includes IL (Internet Link), a
reliable transport protocol simpler than TCP. IL conveys the
essential ideas of reliable communication---sequence numbers,
acknowledgments, retransmission---without TCP's complexity
(window scaling, congestion control, urgent data, etc.), making
it an ideal teaching vehicle.

\section{Other network stacks}

Here are a few network stacks that I considered for this book, but
which I ultimately discarded:
\begin{itemize}

%claude:
\item DataKit was Bell Labs' packet-switching network,
a precursor to the internet within AT\&T. Its ideas influenced
\plan's networking, but DataKit itself is no longer in use.
% unix ancestor? mentioned in Unix Readers

\item XINU's network stack is educational but too simple---it
lacks features like routing and a complete TCP implementation.

\item The Linux network stack is production-quality and
heavily optimized, but enormous. Even the core IP/TCP code
(excluding drivers) is hundreds of thousands of lines.

\item The BSD network stack (especially FreeBSD's) has an
excellent reputation and was the reference implementation of
TCP/IP for decades. Windows even adopted a fork of the BSD
stack at one point.
% FreeBSD especially have strong reputation regarding its network stack.
% apparently Windows rewrite his network stack with a fork of BSD stack
% (can, license is quite permissive)
% see infomagic 94, slacksrc/n/tcpip/BSD lots of sources for lots of network
% programs
However, like Linux, it is far too large for a book.

\item Minix has a network stack, but it runs as a separate
user-space server (microkernel architecture), making it
harder to compare with \plan's in-kernel approach.

\item Mirage\furl{https://github.com/mirage/mirage-tcpip}
is a TCP/IP stack written in OCaml as a unikernel library.
An interesting modern approach, but the OCaml code is
harder to relate to the C-based stacks most programmers
encounter.
% https://github.com/mirage/mirage-tcpip

\end{itemize}

