\section{Getting started}

%bootstrap:
% to get source of network stack, need a working network stack (and OS) :)
% alternative is put it on floppy disk or CDs (that's how Linux was
% originally distributed).

%claude:
To test the network stack, you need \plan running under QEMU
with networking enabled:
\begin{verbatim}
$ qemu-system-i386 -smp 4 -m 512 -kernel $KERNEL \
    -hda dosdisk.img -serial mon:stdio -net nic -net user
\end{verbatim}
% -net nic -net user

%claude:
The [[-net nic -net user]] flags tell QEMU to emulate a network
card and provide a virtual network where the guest (\plan) gets
IP address [[10.0.2.15]], the gateway is [[10.0.2.2]], and a
DNS server is at [[10.0.2.3]].

%claude:
The quickest way to get networking up inside \plan is:
% short version:
\begin{verbatim}
$ ipconfig
$ dns -r
$ cs
$ hget http://www.google.com
\end{verbatim}
% !!it works!! the ipconfig and dns were the commands in my
% plan9.png screenshot used in Principia.nw
% but I have pbs with ping :( can't even ping 8.8.8.8) but 9front too
% for hget to work you also need the 'cs' before (connexion server?)
%
[[ipconfig]] obtains an IP address via DHCP.
[[dns -r]] starts a DNS resolver.
[[cs]] starts the connection server, which translates
network addresses for programs like [[hget]].
Finally, [[hget]] fetches a web page---if this works,
the entire stack (Ethernet, IP, TCP, DNS) is functional.

%alt to dhcp:
% ipconfig -g <gateway-ip> ether /net/ether0 <your-ip> <subnet-mask>
% ipconfig -g 10.0.2.2 ether /net/ether0 10.0.2.15 255.255.255.0

%claude:
To explore the network state in more detail, you can
inspect the [[/net/]] files directly:
% long version
\begin{verbatim}
$ ipconfig
$ cat /net/ipifc/0/status
device /net/ether0 ... 10.0.2.15 /120 10.0.2.0
$ ping 10.0.2.15
0: 2900microsec
1: ...
$ ping 10.0.2.2
...
$ cat /net/iproute
0.0.0.0 /96 10.0.2.2 4 none -
...
$ cat /net/arp
...
$ cat /net/ndb
...
\end{verbatim}

% ping 8.8.8.8 or google ip does not seem to work though.
% maybe QEMU allows TCP/UDB packets but not ICMP (ping) packets.
% update: seems to not work under 9front/qemu either

% cat /net/arp
%  should show the mac adress of machines on LAN as you do the
%  different request. First ipconfig should get 10.0.2.15
%  then after ping 10.0.2.2 you should see it
%  then after dnsquery you should see the one for 10.0.2.3
% cat /net/iproute
%  complex masks though. none vs ifc?
% cat /net/ndb
%  you should see the dns at 10.0.2.3

%claude:
[[/net/ipifc/0/status]] shows the network interface
configuration: which Ethernet device it is bound to and
which IP address was assigned. [[ping]] tests connectivity
by sending ICMP packets. [[/net/iproute]] displays the
routing table, [[/net/arp]] shows the ARP cache (MAC-to-IP
mappings learned from the local network), and [[/net/ndb]]
contains the network database (DNS server address, etc.).
All of these are just files you can [[cat]]---no special
diagnostic commands needed.

%claude:
DNS resolution can be tested interactively with [[dnsquery]]:
\begin{verbatim}
$ dns -r
 starting dns resolver on 10.0.2.15's /net
$ dnsquery
> www.google.com
www.google.com ip 216.58.204.132
\end{verbatim}

% the -r seems to be important. otherwise hget http://iwp9.org/ does
% not work for example

%claude:
You can even make raw TCP connections with [[telnet]] using
\plan's network address syntax \verb+proto!host!port+:
\begin{verbatim}
$ telnet tcp!216.58.204.132!80
GET
\end{verbatim}
%
This opens a TCP connection to Google's IP on port 80
and sends a bare HTTP [[GET]] request---you should see
HTML content in response.

% => get possible html content!
% GET / HTTP/1.0
% => loops forever :(

% ex of IP: iwp9.org: 168.235.82.121

%claude:
For a higher-level test, [[hget]] fetches a URL.
It requires the connection server [[cs]] to translate
hostnames:
\begin{verbatim}
$ cs
$ hget http://www.google.com
\end{verbatim}

% need cs otherwise dns translation does not work in hget
% or telnet;  telnet tcp!www.google.com!80 didn't work before
% cs

%claude:
Finally, for a full web browsing experience under \plan,
you need several cooperating file servers:
% want web!
\begin{verbatim}
$ plumber
$ webcookies
$ webfs
$ abaco
\end{verbatim}
%
[[plumber]] handles inter-application message routing
(mounted on [[/mnt/plumb]]),
[[webcookies]] manages HTTP cookies
(mounted on [[/mnt/webcookies]]),
[[webfs]] provides a file-system interface to the web
(mounted on [[/mnt/web]]),
and [[abaco]] is the actual web browser that reads from
[[webfs]]. This is the \plan philosophy in action:
each service is a separate file server, composed together.

%claude:
Note that the network stack described in this book is
implemented entirely inside the \plan kernel and can only
run under a full \plan system---it is not available through
plan9port. The user-space networking functions ([[dial()]],
[[announce()]], [[listen()]]) do exist in plan9port, but
they are thin wrappers around the host OS's socket interface,
not the \plan [[/net/]] file system described here.

