%claude:
Because this book is made of C source code, you will need
a good knowledge of the C programming language~\cite{k-r}.
The networking code makes heavy use of byte-level manipulation
(packing and unpacking packet headers) and concurrent
programming (kernel processes handling incoming packets).
%
This book is not an introduction to computer networking.
I assume you have a basic understanding of concepts such as
IP addresses, ports, TCP, UDP, Ethernet, and the layered
protocol model. Standard references include Tanenbaum's
{\em Computer Networks}~\cite{tannenbaum-networks},
Comer's {\em Internetworking with TCP/IP}~\cite{comer-tcp},
and Stevens' {\em TCP/IP Illustrated}~\cite{tcp-illustrated}
(for protocol internals) and {\em UNIX Network
Programming}~\cite{unix-network-programming}
(for the programming interface).
%
Reading the \book{Kernel} is strongly recommended: the
network stack runs inside the kernel and uses its facilities
(devices, [[sleep]]/[[wakeup]], kernel processes).
The historical paper {\em The Organization of Networks in
Plan~9}~\cite{network-plan9} is also a useful reference for
the design decisions behind [[/net/]].

%claude:
If, while reading this book, you have specific questions
on the file and ioctl interfaces exposed by the network
stack, I suggest you to consult the manual pages in my
\plan repository. [[docs/man/3/ip]] is the central
reference for the [[/net/]] device hierarchy
([[/net/tcp/]], [[/net/udp/]], [[/net/il/]],
[[/net/ipifc/]], [[/net/iproute]], [[/net/arp]]);
[[docs/man/2/ip]] documents the user-space helper
functions [[parseip]]/[[parseether]]/[[myipaddr]]/[[hnputl]]
used throughout the stack; [[docs/man/2/dial]] and
[[docs/man/8/ipconfig]] document the client and
administration interfaces; [[docs/man/8/ndb]] and
[[docs/man/2/ndb]] cover the network database that backs
name resolution; [[docs/man/8/6in4]] and
[[docs/man/8/aan]] document the tunneling protocols.
%
The [[networking/docs/]] directory
% (sitting next to the companion \book{Network Applications})
contains two papers
essential to this book: [[networking/docs/net/net.pdf]]
(``The Organization of Networks in Plan~9'', the paper
