%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Overview}
%******************************************************************************

%claude:
Before showing the source code of the \plan network stack in
the following chapters, I first give an overview of the general
principles of networking, describe the [[/net/]] file interface,
and explain how the code is organized.

\section{Networking principles}

%claude:
Networking solves a fundamental problem: how to let two
programs on different machines communicate. The solution
involves multiple layers of abstraction, from the physical
signals on a wire to the reliable byte streams that
applications use. The following subsections present these
layers bottom-up, from local networks to reliable
transport---the same order in which the \plan network
stack processes packets.

\subsection{Local area networking}

% local (mac) address, ethernet, local area network
%  write to all, snoop and take when for your (mac) address
% old: ipx?

%\subsection{Physical layer}

%claude:
A {local area network} (LAN) connects machines that are
physically close---in the same room, building, or campus.
The dominant LAN technology is {Ethernet}, where each
machine has a unique hardware address (the {MAC address})
and sends data as {frames} on a shared medium. Every machine
on the LAN sees every frame, but only the one with the
matching destination MAC address accepts it.

%claude:
Ethernet was invented by Robert Metcalfe at Xerox PARC
in~1973 and standardized as IEEE~802.3 in~1983; it
competed against {\sc ibm}'s {\em Token Ring}, Apple's
{\em LocalTalk}, and {\em {\sc fddi}} through the~1990s
and won almost completely by the early~2000s.
%why-win:
The
technical reason was {\em simplicity}: Ethernet's
protocol was far simpler than Token Ring's token-passing
or {\sc fddi}'s dual-ring, which made hardware cheaper to
build and easier to scale to faster speeds. Today's
networks run the same IEEE~802.3 frame format at speeds
from 1\,Gbps at the desktop through 100\,Gbps and
400\,Gbps on datacenter backbones, and the wireless
equivalent Wi-Fi (IEEE~802.11, Wi-Fi~7 shipping in~2024)
uses a close variant of the Ethernet frame format over a
radio medium.

\subsection{Packets and frames}

% Frame.
% packets! and actually whole idea of network abstraction is to
% provide what seems like an arbitrary length or even continuous stream
% of data on top of this fixed packet. A bit similar to file and fs
% which are on top of disk blocks.

% need packets for ethernet as you write to everybody on the "backbone",
% and need fairness.
% (need packet even more for internetworking)

%claude:
Data is sent over networks in discrete chunks called
{packets} (at the IP level) or {frames} (at the Ethernet
level). This is necessary because the network is a shared
resource: if one machine sent a continuous stream, no other
machine could transmit. Fixed-size packets ensure fairness.
%
The whole idea of the network abstraction is to provide
what appears to be a continuous stream of data on top of
these fixed-size packets---similar to how a file system
provides the illusion of continuous files on top of
fixed-size disk blocks.

%claude: %cs-history:
The idea is older than it sounds. Paul Baran at {\sc rand}
proposed packet switching in~1964, Donald Davies at the
UK's National Physical Laboratory independently arrived
at the same idea in~1965, and {\sc arpanet} in~1969 was
the first operational packet-switched network. The
alternative---{\em circuit switching}, with a dedicated
physical path per call---had dominated telephony since the
1890s and lost the contest only gradually: the global
telephone network did not fully migrate to packet-based
voice (VoIP) until roughly~2010. Modern datacenter
networks push the same idea further with {\sc rdma},
which lets a network card write directly into the
destination process's memory without involving the
receiving {\sc cpu}.

%comeback: %claude:
Circuit switching lost to packet switching, but the
desire for circuit-like behavior---predictable, ordered,
reliable connections---keeps returning at higher layers.
TCP provides a virtual ``connection'' on top of
connectionless IP packets; QUIC does the same on top of
UDP. Applications {\em want} circuits even though the
network underneath is pure packet switching, so each
generation reinvents a connection abstraction one layer
up.

\subsection{Internetworking and gateways}

% ip universal address, inter network, routing, gateway, multiple interfaces
% (packets become really useful there because big sharing).
% gateways are really important, and so is having multiple IPs.

% A virtual network.
% A bit similar to memory, where have physical memory but abstracted
% away with virtual memory. In the same way with network have
% physical address and local area network but build on top of that
% virtual addresses and a virtual global network.

%\subsection{Physical versus logical address}
% DNS

%claude:
A LAN only connects nearby machines. To communicate across
LANs, we need {internetworking}: a virtual network built
on top of physical networks. The {Internet Protocol} (IP)
assigns each machine a logical address (the {IP address})
and uses {gateways} (routers) to forward packets between
networks.
%
This is analogous to virtual memory: just as the kernel
builds a virtual address space on top of physical memory,
the IP layer builds a virtual global network on top of
physical local networks. MAC addresses are the ``physical
addresses'' and IP addresses are the ``virtual addresses.''

%claude: %cs-history:
The IP/TCP design was introduced by Vint Cerf and Bob
Kahn in a 1974 paper, and replaced {\sc arpanet}'s
earlier NCP on a single ``flag day,'' 1~January~1983.
The alternative protocols that competed with TCP/IP
through the~1980s---{\sc ccitt}'s X.25, {\sc dec}net,
Novell's {\sc ipx}/{\sc spx}, AppleTalk, Banyan's
VINES---are now all retired or relegated to legacy
compatibility layers. TCP/IP's technical edge was the
{\em end-to-end principle}: keep the network simple
(routers just forward packets, no per-connection state)
and push reliability to the endpoints---which made
routers cheap and the whole system more flexible than
alternatives like X.25 that embedded connection state
inside the network. IPv4's 32-bit address space ran
out in the~2010s, which is why every current network
runs a combination of {\sc nat} ({\em network address
translation}) and the slow ongoing migration to IPv6
(standardized~1998, about~45\% of Google traffic as
of~2024).

\subsection{Reliable communication}

% packets even more important here. cos unreliable. and need more fairness.
% backbone used by many.

% general datagram and specific fragments,
% to abstract away from particular physical link constraints.

% tcp: because route can be complex, and can use different routes,
% so can arrive in different order, so need protocol, ack, retransmit,
% reorder, etc. Tricky.

%claude:
IP provides no guarantees: packets can be lost, duplicated,
reordered, or corrupted. A {reliable transport protocol}
(like TCP or \plan's IL) adds the machinery to provide
an ordered, reliable byte stream on top of this unreliable
foundation. The key mechanisms are {sequence numbers}
(to detect reordering and loss), {acknowledgments}
(to confirm receipt), and {retransmission timers}
(to resend lost packets). Getting this right is one of
the trickiest parts of a network stack, because the
protocol must handle arbitrarily delayed, duplicated,
and reordered packets.

%claude:
This set of mechanisms---sequence numbers, cumulative
acks, and adaptive retransmission---was worked out during
the design of TCP by Cerf, Kahn, and Postel in the
late~1970s and published as RFC~793 in~1981. Every
reliable transport since has borrowed the same toolkit:
\plan's own IL, {\sc sctp} (2007), Google's QUIC (2012,
standardized as RFC~9000 in~2021, and the wire protocol
underneath HTTP/3 that serves roughly a third of all web
traffic today), and the various proprietary reliable-{\sc
udp} protocols used by game engines and VPNs. What changes
from protocol to protocol is how the window and
retransmission timing are tuned, not the core ideas.

\subsection{Flow control and congestion control}
\label{sec:princ-flow-congestion}

%claude:
The mechanisms described above---sequence numbers, acks,
and retransmit timers---solve the {\em reliability}
problem: making sure every byte sent eventually arrives,
in order and uncorrupted. They answer ``did the data get
there?''. A serious reliable transport has to answer two
more questions that are easy to conflate with
reliability yet are entirely distinct. {\em Flow
control} asks ``can the {\em receiver} keep up?''---a
slow consumer talking to a fast producer will see its
receive buffer fill and drop packets even over a
perfectly reliable link. {\em Congestion control} asks
``can the {\em network in the middle} keep up?''---dozens
of senders competing for one bottleneck router will all
see losses and timeouts even if every individual endpoint
is perfectly reliable. Conflating these three concerns is
one of the classic bugs in network code, and the
differing answers to them are what make {\sc tcp} big
and IL small.

%claude:
The standard mechanism for flow control is the {\em
sliding window}. The receiver reports, with every ack,
how many more bytes of data its buffer can still hold
(its {\em receive window}). The sender is not allowed
to have more than that many unacked bytes in flight at
a time and must wait for acknowledgments that free up
window space before sending more. A window of zero
means ``pause''---at which point the sender must
periodically probe the receiver to learn when the
window reopens (the {\em zero-window probe}, because
acks in the reverse direction are not guaranteed to
arrive). The sliding window also doubles as the
retransmission-bookkeeping mechanism: the sender keeps
a copy of every unacked byte in a send buffer, and the
sliding window is the reason that buffer has a bounded
size.

%claude:
Congestion control is a younger idea. In October~1986
the {\sc arpanet} experienced its first {\em congestion
collapse}: bandwidth on the Berkeley--{\sc lbl} link
dropped from~32\,kbps to 40~{\em bits} per second as
every {\sc tcp} endpoint aggressively retransmitted
into an already-saturated router. Van Jacobson's
1988~{\sc sigcomm} paper {\em Congestion Avoidance and
Control} gave {\sc tcp} the four mechanisms still at
its core today: {\em slow start} (ramp the send rate
up from one packet per round trip, doubling every
{\sc rtt}, until a loss occurs); {\em congestion
avoidance} (after a loss, treat the attained rate as
the ``safe'' ceiling and grow additively from there);
{\em fast retransmit} (treat three duplicate acks as a
loss signal instead of waiting for the timer); and
{\em fast recovery} (halve the rate after a fast
retransmit instead of restarting from one). Together
these form an {\sc aimd} policy
(additive-increase/multiplicative-decrease) whose
emergent property, after much theoretical analysis, is
approximate fairness across competing flows sharing a
bottleneck. Modern {\sc tcp} implementations have
replaced Jacobson's original algorithms with variants
matched to today's networks: {\sc cubic} (Linux default
since~2006) uses a cubic function for faster recovery
on long high-bandwidth links; {\sc bbr} (Google, 2016)
abandons loss-based signals altogether and models the
bottleneck bandwidth and {\sc rtt} directly; historical
names worth knowing include Reno, New~Reno, Vegas,
Westwood, and {\sc dctcp}.

%claude:
The fundamental reason congestion control is hard is
that the sender cannot directly observe the network: it
must {\em infer} congestion from the timing and pattern
of losses, and random loss (from a noisy wireless link,
a flaky cable, a bad {\sc nic}) is indistinguishable
from congestion loss at the endpoint level. Getting the
heuristics right is most of the source code of any
modern {\sc tcp} stack. \plan's IL protocol sidesteps
both concerns entirely: it was designed for the Bell
Labs local area networks where packet loss is near-zero
and {\sc rtt} is low, so it needs neither a sliding
receive window (LAN peers have abundant buffer) nor a
congestion-control algorithm (there is no bottleneck
router to congest). This is exactly what lets IL stay
in roughly 1500 lines of C, while \plan's {\sc tcp}
(Chapter~\ref{chap:tcp}) runs to around~3600. Every one
of those extra 2000 lines is either flow control,
congestion control, a larger state machine for the
four-way close handshake, or an adaptive
retransmit timer that must handle much wider {\sc rtt}
variance than IL's simple LAN case.

\subsection{Network stack}

% ip stack goal is to multiplex access to network device.
% and then to demultiplex when receive (by address, by protocol)
% and to provide different encoding protocols providing different
% kinds of services. Also goal is to provide means to configure.

%claude:
The {network stack} is the software that implements all
these layers. Its main job is {multiplexing} on the send
side (many processes share one network device) and
{demultiplexing} on the receive side (incoming packets
must be dispatched to the right process based on addresses
and port numbers). It also provides different protocols
offering different levels of service: UDP for simple
unreliable datagrams, TCP/IL for reliable streams.

%claude:
Every modern operating system has one. The grandparent of
them all is the {\em Berkeley {\sc tcp}/{\sc ip} stack}
written for {\sc bsd}~4.2 in~1983 by Bill Joy and Sam
Leffler, so influential that its code was copied almost
verbatim into the first Windows~NT networking subsystem.
Linux has its own independent reimplementation
(started~1991, now the dominant stack on servers), macOS
descends from FreeBSD's fork, and embedded systems often
use [[lwip]] (2001) as a size-conscious alternative. The
modern high-performance trend is {\em kernel bypass}:
frameworks like DPDK and Linux's XDP run the protocol
work in user space or in eBPF programs on the network
card, bypassing the traditional kernel stack for
latency-critical paths.

\subsection{Ports and demultiplexing}
\label{sec:princ-ports}

%claude:
When a packet arrives at a machine, the network stack has
to decide which of the many processes running on that
machine should receive it. The IP address alone is not
enough---every process on the machine shares the same IP
address. The extra piece of identification is a 16-bit
number called a {\em port}: each transport-layer packet
({\sc tcp} or {\sc udp}) carries a source port and a
destination port in its header, and the network stack
demultiplexes incoming packets by looking up the
destination port in a per-protocol table of listening
conversations. Ports are a purely transport-layer
concept---they do not exist in {\sc ip}, Ethernet, or any
layer below---and they are what lets a single machine run
a web server, an {\sc ssh} daemon, and a {\sc dns}
resolver simultaneously on the same interface.

%claude:
The 16-bit port space is traditionally divided into three
ranges. {\em Well-known} ports (0 through~1023, including
{\sc ssh} on~22, {\sc smtp} on~25, {\sc dns} on~53,
{\sc http} on~80, {\sc https} on~443) are assigned by
{\sc iana} to standard services and are historically
restricted to root-owned processes on \unix, so only a
privileged daemon can bind to them. {\em Registered}
ports (1024 through~49151) are assigned by {\sc iana} to
specific applications on request but are usable by any
process. {\em Ephemeral} or {\em dynamic} ports
(49152--65535 by current {\sc iana} recommendation,
though Linux defaults to 32768--60999) are what the
kernel hands out when a client calls [[connect]] without
binding a specific source port first. The ephemeral range
is what lets thousands of outgoing connections from the
same client coexist on the same local address: each new
[[connect]] is assigned a fresh ephemeral port, so the
4-tuple {\em (src~addr, src~port, dst~addr, dst~port)} is
unique and the receiving side can demultiplex return
traffic back to the right conversation.

%claude:
\plan exposes ports through the file interface from
Section~\ref{sec:princ-file-vs-socket}: when a client
writes [[connect 192.168.1.1!80]] to a new conversation's
[[ctl]] file, the kernel picks an ephemeral source port
automatically; when a server writes [[announce tcp!*!80]],
it binds to port~80 on every interface. The
[[/net/tcp/42/local]] and [[/net/tcp/42/remote]] files
expose the resulting endpoints as plain text. Ephemeral
port selection and the privileged-port rule are both
handled entirely inside the [[devip]] kernel file
server---there is no separate [[bind]] syscall and no
[[setsockopt]] with [[SO_REUSEADDR]]; port reuse is a
policy of the [[ctl]] command parser, not a property of a
socket object.

\subsection{Layers}
% OSI

%claude:
Network stacks are organized in {layers}, each building
on the one below:
\begin{verbatim}
  +-------------------------------+
  |  Applications (telnet, hget)  |
  +-------------------------------+
  |  Transport (TCP, UDP, IL)     |
  +-------------------------------+
  |  Internet (IP, ICMP)          |
  +-------------------------------+
  |  Link (Ethernet, ARP)         |
  +-------------------------------+
  |  Physical (NIC hardware)      |
  +-------------------------------+
\end{verbatim}
%
Each layer adds its own header to the data (encapsulation)
and strips it on the receiving side. The \plan network
stack follows this layered structure closely, with each
protocol implemented as a [[Proto]] module.

%claude:
The layering model is itself a design decision. The
\unix-family model shown above has 4 or 5 layers and grew
organically out of the TCP/IP implementation at Berkeley.
Its rival, the ISO {\em Open Systems Interconnection}
(OSI) model (1984), has 7 layers---adding session,
presentation, and application as separate layers above
transport---and was the {\em official} international
standard for networking through the late~1980s;
%why-win:
TCP/IP
won in the market despite the official push for OSI,
largely because TCP/IP had running code and a deployed
network years before OSI had a usable implementation.
Modern networks routinely blur these clean boundaries:
QUIC runs a full reliable transport inside {\sc udp}
datagrams (transport inside transport), service meshes
like Istio add an application-level routing layer on top
of TCP, and software-defined networking moves the control
logic out of the forwarding path entirely.

\subsection{File interface versus socket API}
\label{sec:princ-file-vs-socket}

%claude:
The dominant way to do networking on every mainstream
operating system today is the {\em socket {\sc api}},
introduced by {\sc bsd}~4.2 in~1983 and subsequently
inherited by Linux, macOS, Solaris, and Windows (as
Winsock2). Conceptually a socket is a special kind of
file descriptor that the kernel tracks through its own
object system: you create it with
[[socket(AF_INET, SOCK_STREAM, 0)]], set it up with
[[bind]]/[[connect]]/[[listen]]/[[accept]], send and
receive bytes with
[[send]]/[[recv]]/[[sendto]]/[[recvfrom]], configure it
with [[setsockopt]] (passing integer option codes like
[[SO_REUSEADDR]] or [[TCP_NODELAY]]), and multiplex
{\sc i/o} with a dedicated primitive---[[select]],
[[poll]], [[epoll]], [[kqueue]], or Windows {\sc iocp}.
The {\sc api} has something like thirty entry points
and dozens of type and option constants; it forms a
dedicated namespace of concepts bolted onto the
\unix file model without quite fitting it (a file
descriptor to a socket behaves differently from a
file descriptor to a regular file in a hundred subtle
ways).

%claude:
\plan makes the same choice for graphics and for almost
every other kernel service: expose the subsystem as a
small file tree rather than as a dedicated {\sc api}.
For networking, the tree is rooted at [[/net/]], with
one subtree per protocol ([[/net/tcp]], [[/net/udp]],
[[/net/il]]). Opening a connection is three ordinary
file operations: read [[/net/tcp/clone]] (which
allocates a fresh conversation directory, say
[[/net/tcp/42/]], and returns an open file descriptor
to its [[ctl]] file); write a string like
[[connect 192.168.1.1!80]] to [[/net/tcp/42/ctl]]; then open and
read or write [[/net/tcp/42/data]] for the byte stream.
Configuration uses human-readable text commands written
to [[ctl]] (e.g., [[keepalive 30]]); status is
text read from sibling files like
[[/net/tcp/42/status]], [[/net/tcp/42/local]], and
[[/net/tcp/42/remote]]; {\sc i/o} multiplexing uses the
same file-descriptor select machinery as any other
file. There is no socket type, no [[setsockopt]], no
[[ioctl]]---just files.

%claude:
The consequences show up in surprising places. Any
programming language that can read and write files
gets networking for free, without an {\sc ffi} to a
socket library; \plan's shell [[rc]] can open a
{\sc tcp} connection with nothing but file redirection.
Network services can be {\em delegated} through
namespaces: [[bind]]ing or [[mount]]ing another
machine's [[/net]] over your own gives you its network
stack, which is one way \plan implements what
elsewhere requires a {\sc vpn}, [[ssh]] port
forwarding, or a container network namespace.
Firewalling a process is just removing
[[/net/tcp/clone]] from its namespace---no
[[iptables]], no packet filter, no seccomp rules to
maintain---because without [[clone]] the process
cannot allocate a new conversation in the first place.
And standard tools like [[cat]], [[grep]], [[wc]], and
[[dd]] work unmodified on network connections, which
is why \plan has no dedicated [[netcat]]: every
program is already [[netcat]] by composition.

%claude:
The historical cost of this design was performance:
routing every network read and write through the
file-system protocol was slower than calling a
dedicated socket syscall on Linux or {\sc bsd}. On
modern hardware that gap has largely closed, and
mainstream operating systems have themselves drifted
toward file-like networking: Linux offers abstract
sockets in the filesystem namespace, [[/proc/net/*]]
for stack introspection, [[netlink]] for configuration,
and most recently [[io_uring]] for a single unified
async interface that treats sockets and files alike.
The interesting trade-off today is less about raw
performance than about {\em code size} and
{\em namespace composability}: \plan's whole networking
stack fits in roughly 22\,000 lines largely because it
did not need to grow a dedicated socket {\sc api} and
its corresponding kernel object layer. The rest of
this chapter's [[/net]] file-server interface section
is what that choice looks like in concrete terms.

\subsection{The end-to-end argument}
\label{sec:princ-end-to-end}

%claude:
The {\em end-to-end principle}, mentioned earlier as
TCP/IP's technical edge over X.25, was given its
canonical articulation by Jerome Saltzer, David Reed,
and David Clark in a 1984 paper titled {\em ``End-to-End
Arguments in System Design''}---one of the most cited
papers in the networking literature. The argument is
deceptively simple: {\em a function can only be
completely and correctly implemented with the knowledge
and help of the application standing at the endpoints;
providing that function as a feature of the
communication system itself is not possible.} In other
words, the network cannot guarantee delivery without
the receiver confirming receipt to the sender, so any
reliability mechanism inside the network is
redundant---the endpoints must verify anyway. The
consequence is that routers should do as little as
possible (forward packets, discard corrupted ones) and
leave everything else---ordering, retransmission,
encryption, authentication---to the endpoints.

%claude:
This one principle explains most of the Internet's
architecture. Routers are cheap and simple because they
are stateless packet forwarders. New transport protocols
({\sc sctp}, QUIC) can be deployed by updating the
endpoints alone, without touching a single router.
End-to-end encryption ({\sc tls}, {\sc ssh}) works
because the network {\em cannot} inspect the
payload---the ultimate enforcement of the principle via
cryptography. But the principle has been under pressure
for decades. {\em Middleboxes}---{\sc nat} (which
rewrites addresses and breaks direct
endpoint-to-endpoint connectivity), firewalls (which
inspect and filter), deep-packet inspection (which reads
content), {\sc cdn}s (which cache and serve on behalf of
the origin)---all violate the end-to-end argument to
varying degrees, and the modern Internet has far more
middleboxes than the original designers imagined. The
tension between ``dumb network, smart endpoints'' and
``the network needs to inspect traffic for security and
performance'' is one of the defining architectural
debates of the 2020s.

%claude:
\plan's networking takes the end-to-end argument further
than most \unix systems by making the endpoints even more
autonomous. Because network connections are just files
(Section~\ref{sec:princ-file-vs-socket}), and because
namespaces are per-process, a \plan machine can rearrange
its own view of the network without any middlebox: import
another machine's [[/net]] to tunnel through it, or
restrict a process's [[/net]] to firewall it, all
without touching the network itself. The ``intelligence''
that elsewhere lives in {\sc nat} boxes and firewall
appliances is pushed to the endpoints---exactly where the
end-to-end argument says it belongs.

