\subsection{Routing forest}

%claude:
The routing table is a forest of $2^{10} = 1024$ ternary
search trees. The destination IP address is hashed (via
[[V4H]]) to select a root, then the tree is walked using
address-range comparisons: left for ranges entirely below,
right for ranges entirely above, and mid for overlapping
ranges (more specific routes). This structure supports
longest-prefix matching efficiently.

%claude:
Pictorially, [[Fs.v4root]] is a fan-out array of 1024 tree roots,
each pointing to a ternary-tree of [[Route]] nodes:
\begin{verbatim}
 Fs.v4root[]       (each Route holds V4route {address, endaddress, gate})
 +--------+
 |   0    |---> nil
 +--------+
 |   1    |---> [10.0.0.0 .. 10.0.0.255 -> ether0]
 +--------+        |   \
 |  ...   |      left  mid---> [10.0.0.42 .. 10.0.0.42 -> ppp0]  (more specific)
 +--------+        |   \
 | V4H(ip)|---> [ range containing ip ]
 +--------+        /   \
 | ...    |     left  right
 +--------+
 | 1023   |---> ...
 +--------+
\end{verbatim}
The [[mid]] pointer is what makes this a \emph{ternary} tree rather
than a binary one: when a new range sits strictly inside an existing
range (e.g.\ a /32 host route inside a /24 subnet route), it hangs
off [[mid]]. [[v4lookup]] descends [[mid]] as long as the address
fits, so it naturally returns the most specific match---no separate
longest-prefix-match pass is needed. Compared to Linux's FIB\_TRIE
(a patricia trie with path compression) or BSD's original radix
tree, \plan's forest is cruder but short and debuggable.

<<[[Fs(kernel)]] routing fields>>=
// hash<ip, ref<Route>> where hash function is V4H
Route *v4root[1<<Lroot];  /* v4 routing forest */
@
% >>

<<constant [[Lroot]]>>=
/* 2^Lroot trees in the root table */
Lroot=    10,
@


