\subsection{Mounting the ethernet device}

%claude:
Mounting the Ethernet device (\verb+bind #l0 /net+) triggers
[[etherattach]], which looks up controller 0 in the [[etherxx]]
array and calls its [[attach]] method. This populates
[[/net/ether0/]] with files for reading/writing Ethernet
frames, the MAC address ([[/net/ether0/addr]]), and
statistics. The MAC address can be read with
\verb+cat /net/ether0/addr+.

% see kernel init.c
% bind #l -a /net
%  bind_safe("#l0", "/net", MAFTER); // ether (and dev 0)

% => /net/ether0
% => /net/ether0/addr to get MAC address

% actually populated with many things already, 0/, 1/, 2/ with
% different x/type values

% /net/ether0/stats  give you also your mac address at the very end

% will mount multiple devices for gateways.

% ??? sysbind?? -> <> (as attach <- etherdevtab?.attach <- toplevel)
<<function [[etherattach]]>>=
Chan*
etherattach(char* spec)
{
    ulong ctlrno;
    char *p;
    Chan *chan;

    ctlrno = 0;
    if(spec && *spec){
        ctlrno = strtoul(spec, &p, 0);
        if((ctlrno == 0 && p == spec) || *p || (ctlrno >= MaxEther))
            error(Ebadarg);
    }
    if(etherxx[ctlrno] == nil)
        error(Enodev);

    chan = devattach('l', spec);
    if(waserror()){
        chanfree(chan);
        nexterror();
    }
    chan->dev = ctlrno;
    if(etherxx[ctlrno]->attach)
        // Ethernet controller dispatch
        etherxx[ctlrno]->attach(etherxx[ctlrno]);

    poperror();
    return chan;
}
@
% #l0 => spec = 0

% the attach method

\section{User side}

%claude:
From user space, ``initialization'' means two different things
depending on whether you are the administrator or the
application. The administrator runs [[ipconfig]] (typically at
boot) to bind an interface, assign an IP address, and install
a default route---this populates [[/net/ipifc/0/]],
[[/net/arp]], and [[/net/iproute]] so that subsequent network
activity has somewhere to go. An ordinary application does
something much smaller: it opens [[/net/tcp/clone]], writes a
[[connect]] line, and starts reading and writing. The kernel
work of allocating a conversation, allocating sequence numbers,
and driving the handshake state machine happens inside those
[[write]] and [[read]] syscalls---there is no separate
``initialize TCP'' step because everything the application
needs is plumbed through the file interface.

\subsection{Connect manually}

%claude:
A user program connects manually by opening
[[/net/tcp/clone]] (which returns a conversation number),
then writing \verb+connect 10.0.0.1!80+ to
[[/net/tcp/N/ctl]], and reading/writing [[/net/tcp/N/data]].
The [[dial]] library function wraps this sequence,
optionally consulting the connection server for name
resolution.

