\section{Features}

%claude:
It is worth stepping back and listing what ``reliable'' actually
means in a protocol like IL (or TCP). Each of the subsections
below corresponds to one promise the protocol makes to its user
and one machinery in the code that implements it. Taken
together, they are the difference between UDP and IL: UDP gives
you a best-effort datagram, and you are on your own if it is
lost, corrupted, delivered twice, or delivered out of order. IL
fills those four gaps with four separate mechanisms---a
checksum for corruption, sequence numbers for ordering, acks
plus retransmission for loss, and a per-connection sequence
window for duplicates---plus adaptive timeouts to tune
retransmission, and keep-alive probes to detect a dead peer.
None of these pieces is novel; what is notable is how small the
IL implementation stays relative to TCP by {omitting} the
features that would not fit in this list (congestion control,
urgent data, byte-stream reassembly, window scaling).

