%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Standard Reliable Communication: TCP}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:tcp}

% TCP in 30 instructions? from van jacobson himself!
%http://www.pdl.cmu.edu/mailinglists/ips/mail/msg00133.html?

% RFC 793, Transmission Control Protocol

%claude:
TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) is the heavy-duty reliable
transport: it provides ordered, byte-stream delivery with
flow control, congestion avoidance, and retransmission.
The implementation is the most complex protocol in the stack,
with a state machine (SYN, ESTABLISHED, FIN-WAIT, etc.),
sliding windows, round-trip time estimation, and Van Jacobson's
congestion control algorithms.

%claude:
I do not cover the full TCP implementation in this book. Every
important idea---connection state, sequence numbers, acks,
retransmission, adaptive timers---already appears in IL
(see Chapter~\ref{chap:il}), so the previous chapter is the
real pedagogical vehicle. What TCP adds on top of IL's core
is mostly a set of optimizations (Van Jacobson congestion
avoidance, slow start, fast retransmit), a more complex state
machine for the four-way close handshake (FIN-WAIT-1, FIN-WAIT-2,
CLOSE-WAIT, TIME-WAIT), and byte-stream instead of datagram
semantics. Each of those is worth an article in its own right
but does not change the overall shape of the code. Reading
[[tcp.c]] after finishing the IL chapter is mostly an exercise
in matching IL structures to their TCP counterparts.

<<function [[tcpinit]]>>=
void
tcpinit(Fs *fs)
{
    Proto *tcp;
    Tcppriv *tpriv;

    tcp = smalloc(sizeof(Proto));
    tpriv = tcp->priv = smalloc(sizeof(Tcppriv));

    tcp->name = "tcp";
    tcp->connect = tcpconnect;
    tcp->announce = tcpannounce;
    tcp->ctl = tcpctl;
    tcp->state = tcpstate;
    tcp->create = tcpcreate;
    tcp->close = tcpclose;
    tcp->rcv = tcpiput;
    tcp->advise = tcpadvise;
    tcp->stats = tcpstats;
    tcp->inuse = tcpinuse;
    tcp->gc = tcpgc;

    tcp->ipproto = IP_TCPPROTO;
    tcp->nc = scalednconv();
    tcp->ptclsize = sizeof(Tcpctl);
    tpriv->stats[MaxConn] = tcp->nc;

    Fsproto(fs, tcp);
}
@

