%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Remote Procedure Call: 9P}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:rpc}

%critique of RPC:
%https://www.cs.vu.nl/~ast/publications/euteco-1988.pdf

%claude:
9P is \plan's file protocol---the wire format for all file
operations (open, read, write, stat, etc.). Every file server
in \plan speaks 9P, and [[mount]] connects a 9P-speaking
server to the local namespace. The marshalling code for 9P
messages ([[convS2M]], [[convM2S]]) lives in \book{Libcore}.

\section{RPC and wire-protocol principles}
\label{sec:princ-9p}

%claude:
A {\em remote procedure call} ({\sc rpc}) is the
networking generalization of a local function call: the
caller wants some work done elsewhere and receives a
result, with the network transport and the argument
serialization hidden behind an {\sc api} that looks the
same as an in-process call. Designing an {\sc rpc}
system forces a handful of decisions that every protocol
has to answer, even when it answers them silently:
{\em what is the transport} ({\sc tcp}, {\sc udp}, Unix
domain socket, {\sc http}, a named pipe);
{\em what is the encoding} of arguments and results
(binary struct vs text, self-describing vs schema-required);
{\em how are errors represented} (status codes, typed
exceptions, free-form strings); {\em is the call
synchronous} (caller blocks) {\em or asynchronous /
streaming} (caller sends many requests at once);
{\em what state does the server keep} per client; and
{\em how are types agreed on} between peers (schema file
compiled in advance? runtime discovery? no schema at all?).
Different answers to these questions yield wildly
different protocols, and each {\sc rpc} system's choice
of defaults shapes every application built on top of it.

%claude: %cs-history:
The first widely deployed {\sc rpc} system was Sun
{\sc rpc}, designed in~1984 by Bob Lyon at Sun
Microsystems for {\sc nfs}. It runs over {\sc tcp} or
{\sc udp}, uses a binary encoding called {\sc xdr}
({\em eXternal Data Representation}), and provides a
code generator called [[rpcgen]] that turns a [[.x]]
schema file into client and server stubs---the blueprint
that almost every subsequent binary {\sc rpc} has
followed. {\sc dce}~{\sc rpc} (1990, descended from
Apollo's {\sc ncs}) added an {\sc idl} compiler and was
later adapted by Microsoft as {\sc msrpc}, the plumbing
under {\sc dcom}, {\sc com}, and half the Windows
{\sc api}. {\sc corba} (1991) tried to unify all of this
under a language-neutral distributed-object model and
became notorious for its complexity. On the text side,
{\sc xml-rpc} (1998) was Dave Winer's ``send {\sc xml}
over {\sc http} and call a method'' hack, which morphed
into {\sc soap} by the early~2000s before everyone gave
up and switched to {\sc json-rpc} and then to {\sc rest}
(Roy Fielding's 2000 dissertation about what {\sc http}
already gave you for free). The current generation is
mostly binary again: {\sc grpc} (Google, 2016) with
Protocol Buffers, Apache Thrift (Facebook, 2007),
Cap'n~Proto (Kenton Varda, 2013), Avro (Hadoop, 2009),
and MessagePack---all schema-based, all
code-generator-driven, all fighting the same trade-offs
Sun {\sc rpc} already confronted in~1984.

%claude:
9P takes a radically different position in this design
space. It is not a general-purpose {\sc rpc} at all: it
is specifically the {\em wire protocol for the file
system API}, so its message set is small because it has
to model only whatever the \plan kernel's file interface
does. The entire protocol is around a dozen request
types, each with a matching reply: [[Tversion]]/[[Rversion]]
to negotiate protocol version and maximum message size,
[[Tauth]]/[[Rauth]] to set up an authentication
[[fid]], [[Tattach]]/[[Rattach]] to open a session and
obtain the [[fid]] for a tree root, [[Twalk]]/[[Rwalk]]
to descend one or more path components from a [[fid]],
[[Topen]]/[[Ropen]] to open a file for reading or
writing, [[Tcreate]]/[[Rcreate]] to create a new file,
[[Tread]]/[[Rread]] and [[Twrite]]/[[Rwrite]] for
{\sc i/o}, [[Tclunk]]/[[Rclunk]] to release a [[fid]],
[[Tremove]]/[[Rremove]] to delete a file,
[[Tstat]]/[[Rstat]] and [[Twstat]]/[[Rwstat]] for
get-metadata and set-metadata, and [[Tflush]]/[[Rflush]]
to cancel a pending request. The critical concept is the
{\em fid} (file identifier): a client-chosen 32-bit
integer that the server associates with one of its file
objects for the duration of the session, much like a
\unix file descriptor but allocated by the client rather
than by the server. Once a [[fid]] is attached to a root,
the client walks, opens, reads, and writes through that
[[fid]], and all of 9P's state lives in the server's
[[fid]]-to-file mapping. The encoding is hand-written in
[[libcore]]'s [[convS2M]] and [[convM2S]] functions---no
code generator, no {\sc idl}, no schema file---because
the message set is small enough that writing twelve
marshal/unmarshal pairs by hand takes less code than
adopting a code-generator framework. The chapter that
follows covers the server side that listens for 9P
requests, with the client side living in the kernel's
[[devmnt]] driver from \book{Kernel} and the
marshalling in \book{Libcore}.

% See Libcore.nw

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Network File System: [[exportfs]]}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:nfs}
% the logical conclusion for all of that.

%claude:
[[exportfs]] is the logical culmination of \plan's
``everything is a file'' design: it serves a local
namespace over the network via 9P, allowing a remote
machine to access your files, devices, and even your
window system.

\section{Network filesystem principles}
\label{sec:princ-netfs}

%claude:
Before diving into [[exportfs]], it helps to step back
and look at what a {\em network filesystem} actually has
to do. The basic requirement---access files on another
machine---sounds like ``just send bytes over a socket,''
but real networked file access requires {transparency}
(a program should not need to know whether a file is
local or remote), {consistency} (what happens when two
machines modify the same file simultaneously?),
{caching} (reading every byte from the network is too
slow), {authentication} (who is allowed to access
what?), {directory operations} (listing, creating,
renaming), and a model for what a remote file
{\em is} (does the remote side track open files? how are
locks propagated?). The answers to these questions
determine whether the system feels like a fast local
disk or like a slow web service.

%claude: %cs-history:
Network filesystems have been a research topic since the
early~1980s, and each generation made different
trade-offs. {\em Sun {\sc nfs}} (1984) was designed to
be {\em stateless}: the server keeps no per-client
state, so a crashed client never corrupts the server and
a crashed server can restart without notifying anyone.
The price is that {\sc nfs} cannot implement {\sc posix}
open-file semantics faithfully, and cross-client
consistency is loose. {\em {\sc smb}}/{\em {\sc cifs}}
(Microsoft, from~1984) took the opposite choice---explicitly
stateful with per-client session state and byte-range
locks---to match Windows file-sharing semantics.
{\em Andrew File System} ({\sc afs}, {\sc cmu}, 1983)
introduced aggressive client-side caching with
server-issued {\em callback promises}: the server tells
each client which files it has cached and revokes those
callbacks when the file is modified on another client.
{\em Coda} ({\sc cmu}, 1987) extended {\sc afs} with
{\em disconnected operation}: a laptop can keep a local
copy, work offline, and reconcile on reconnect. The
current generation---{\em Ceph}, {\em Lustre},
{\em GlusterFS}---went distributed, spreading storage
across many servers for capacity and fault tolerance.
Every one of these systems has its own wire protocol,
its own kernel module on every client, and its own
configuration model.

%claude:
\plan gets all of that for free by exploiting the fact
that it already speaks 9P to its {\em local} file
system. If every application reads and writes through
9P anyway, then a {\em remote} file server is just a 9P
server accessible over a network connection instead of
a local pipe. No new protocol, no new kernel module, no
new abstraction: [[exportfs]] is a user-level program
that accepts 9P messages on standard input (typically
from a network connection), dispatches them against a
{\em local} namespace (whatever subtree of [[/]] the
invoker chose), and writes the 9P replies back out. The
client side is equally simple: [[mount]] an
[[exportfs]] connection the same way you mount any
other 9P server, and the remote tree appears in the
client's namespace. There is nothing filesystem-specific
about [[exportfs]] at all---the protocol work lives in
9P (Chapter~\ref{chap:rpc}) and the server-side adapter
from local-file-access to 9P is just a handful of
dispatch functions.

%claude:
The more interesting twist is what [[exportfs]] enables
when combined with \plan's per-process namespaces. The
[[cpu]] command runs a shell on a remote machine but,
crucially, arranges for [[exportfs]] to serve {\em your}
local namespace over the network {\em back} to that
remote shell. The remote [[cpu]] session then sees your
local home directory, your local [[/dev]], your local
[[/net]], even your local window system---because all
of those are just 9P-speaking files that the remote
shell can reach through the 9P connection. This inverts
the traditional client-server model: rather than your
local machine being a client of remote services, the
remote machine becomes a client of {\em your} local
services, and your entire environment follows you to
any machine on the network. The trick is impossible on
\unix-family systems because they do not have
first-class per-process namespaces or a universal wire
protocol that every file-like object already speaks.
The rest of this chapter walks through the [[exportfs]]
code, which turns out to be mostly a server loop
translating incoming 9P messages into local
[[open]]/[[read]]/[[write]]/[[close]] calls against the
chosen local subtree.

%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Name Resolution: DNS}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:dns}
% code of ndb/ here and of dns and cs?
%TODO? move earlier? pretty fundamental

%claude:
This chapter covers the code that turns human-readable
names like [[mail.example.com]] into IP addresses, and
the name-resolution infrastructure that supports it. In
\plan, this work lives in a user-level file server---the
{\em connection server} ([[cs]])---rather than a [[libc]]
function, so clients interact with it through the file
interface rather than by calling [[getaddrinfo]] or
[[gethostbyname]].

\section{Name resolution principles}
\label{sec:princ-dns}

%claude:
Every layer in the network stack uses numeric
identifiers: Ethernet has 48-bit {\sc mac} addresses,
{\sc ip} has 32-bit (or 128-bit) addresses, transport
protocols have 16-bit ports. None of these are what
humans type into a browser or email client. {\em Name
resolution} is the bridge: the system that lets a human
type [[mail.example.com]] and get back
[[142.251.46.206]]. The question of how that bridge
works is deceptively deep, because it has to scale from
a handful of machines in a lab to hundreds of millions
of hosts on the public Internet, with administrative
control spread across uncoordinated organizations.

%claude:
The simplest name-resolution scheme is a {\em flat
file}: the [[/etc/hosts]] file on \unix (and
[[C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts]] on Windows)
maps each name to an address directly. This works for a
small network but breaks down at scale---every machine
needs a complete copy, and updates must be propagated
manually.
%cs-history:
The response, standardized as {\sc rfc}
1034/1035 in~1987 by Paul Mockapetris, is the
{\em Domain Name System} ({\sc dns}): a {\em
hierarchical} namespace where each level of the
dot-separated name corresponds to a level of
administrative delegation. The root zone (managed by
{\sc iana}) delegates each top-level domain
({\sc tld}---[[com]], [[org]], [[edu]], country codes
like [[fr]] or [[jp]]) to one or more authoritative name
servers; those in turn delegate second-level domains
([[google.com]], [[wikipedia.org]]) to the
organizations that registered them. No single machine
holds the whole map---each authoritative server is
responsible only for its own sub-tree---and
administrative boundaries are exactly the delegation
points.

%claude:
A client asking ``what is the address of
[[mail.example.com]]?'' can resolve the name in two
ways. {\em Iterative} resolution starts at a root
server, which replies ``I don't know, but here is the
authoritative server for [[com]]''; that one points at
the authoritative server for [[example.com]], which
points at the one for [[mail.example.com]], and so on
until the leaf is reached. {\em Recursive} resolution,
the pattern most clients actually use, outsources the
walk to a separate {\em recursive resolver} (at your
{\sc isp}, on your router, or at a public service like
[[8.8.8.8]] or [[1.1.1.1]]): the client asks one
question and the resolver does the iterative work. DNS
servers return {\em resource records} tagged with a
type---[[A]] (IPv4 address), [[AAAA]] (IPv6), [[CNAME]]
(alias), [[MX]] (mail exchanger), [[NS]] (nameserver
delegation), [[PTR]] (reverse lookup), [[TXT]]
(free-form, used for {\sc spf}, {\sc dkim}, and domain
verification), [[SRV]] (service discovery)---each
carrying a {\em time-to-live} ({\sc ttl}) that tells
resolvers how long they may cache the answer. Aggressive
caching at every level of the hierarchy is what keeps
the root and {\sc tld} servers from collapsing under
load.

%claude:
\plan takes its usual simplifying stance: rather than
expose name resolution as a library function every
program must call, it runs a user-level file server
called the {\em connection server} ([[cs]]) that
clients query through the file interface, in exactly
the same way they query [[/net/tcp]]
(Section~\ref{sec:princ-file-vs-socket}). When a program
calls [[dial("tcp!mail.example.com!25")]] from
\book{Libcore}, the [[dial]] implementation writes the
string to [[cs]]'s request file; [[cs]] first consults
the local network database ([[/lib/ndb/local]]) for
static overrides, and falls back to {\sc dns} for
anything it does not find. DNS proper is implemented as
a second user-level server that talks to upstream
name servers over {\sc udp} on port~53, parses the
binary response records, caches them, and returns the
result to [[cs]]. The whole thing is ordinary user-space
code accessed through the file interface, with no
kernel syscalls and no linked-in resolver library:
neither [[getaddrinfo]] nor [[gethostbyname]] exists in
\plan at all. The rest of this chapter walks through the
[[ndb]] parser, the [[cs]] dispatch logic, and the
{\sc dns} client that does the actual RFC~1035 protocol
work.

